In our previous exploration, The Great Illusion of JavaScript, we uncovered a massive secret. JavaScript only has one hand. It can only execute one line of code at a time on its single main thread, known as the Call Stack.
To fake multitasking, JavaScript hands heavy, time-consuming tasks over to the web browser’s background workers (Web APIs). When the browser finishes the work, it puts the instructions in a waiting line until the main thread is completely empty.
Now, we face the next big question: How do we actually write the instructions to make this happen, when do we use each method, and what generates them?
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Over the years, developers invented three distinct ways to tell JavaScript to wait for a background task. Each new method fixed the painful mistakes of the previous one. To understand them, let us step back into the real world.
The Setup: The Ordering System
Imagine placing a complex parcel order at a busy food street in Karachi. You pay the cashier, but they do not cook the food. They must hand the task off to the kitchen in the back.
How does the cashier let you know when your food is finally ready? Historically, developers have tried three different communication systems to handle this waiting period.
1. The “Call Me” System (Callbacks)
In the early days, you would place your order, hand the cashier a piece of paper with your phone number, and say, “I am going to sit down. Call me when the food is ready.”
You gave the kitchen a specific instruction to execute only after the background work was finished.
What is it? In JavaScript, passing a function into another function to be executed later is called a Callback.
How does it work?
// 1. We write the instruction (the callback)
function processFile(fileData) {
console.log("File downloaded! Now processing...");
}// 2. We hand it off to a background task
downloadFile("https://example.com/data", processFile);
When are Callbacks actually used today? Even though it is the oldest method, callbacks are still the absolute standard for two specific things:

• DOM Events: Waiting for a user to interact with the screen. (e.g., button.addEventListener('click', myCallback))

• Timers: Using the browser’s built-in clocks. (e.g., setTimeout(myCallback, 1000))
Why did it fail for complex tasks? (The Pyramid of Doom) Callbacks work perfectly for a single task. But real applications require multiple steps in an exact order. Imagine you must connect to a database, fetch a specific user, fetch their posts, and then calculate analytics.
Because you cannot move to step 2 until step 1 finishes, you must nest callbacks inside of callbacks.
connectToDatabase(function(connection) {
fetchUser(connection, "Naveen", function(user) {
fetchUserPosts(user.id, function(posts) {
calculateAnalytics(posts, function(analytics) {
console.log("Finally done! Here is the data:", analytics);
});
});
});
});Look at the shape of that code. It forms a sideways triangle. Developers universally call this Callback Hell. It is incredibly difficult to read and a nightmare to maintain. The community desperately needed a better way.
2. The Buzzer System (Promises)
To fix the messy nested phone calls, the system upgraded. Now, when you order, the cashier hands you a physical plastic buzzer.
You do not have your food yet, but you have a physical object in your hand that represents the promise of food. You can hold it. If the buzzer flashes green, your food is ready. If the kitchen runs out of ingredients, the buzzer flashes red.
What is it? A Promise is a special JavaScript object. It is a physical placeholder that represents the eventual success or failure of an asynchronous background task.
Manually Creating a Promise (The Factory)
Before we use a Promise, we must understand how it is born. If you are building your own tools, you create a Promise object using the new Promise() constructor.
This constructor gives you two special functions: resolve (turn the buzzer green) and reject (turn the buzzer red). The Promise safely encapsulates the background work.
const myFoodOrder = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
console.log("1. Kitchen is starting the order..."); // Simulating a background task (like cooking) that takes 3 seconds
setTimeout(function() {
let isFoodAvailable = true;
if (isFoodAvailable) {
// Task successful! Pass the data outside (Green Light)
resolve({ item: "Biryani", status: "Ready" });
} else {
// Task failed! Pass the error outside (Red Light)
reject("Sorry, we ran out of rice.");
}
}, 3000);
});
What generates it automatically? You will rarely write the new Promise() code above. Modern web tools and libraries are built to return Promises to you automatically.

• The fetch() API: Asking the browser to download data instantly hands you a Promise.

• Database Libraries: Asking MongoDB or PostgreSQL to find a user instantly hands you a Promise.
Consuming the Promise (Flattening the Pyramid)
Now that we have our Promise object, we wait for it to flash. We use .then() for a green success, and .catch() for a red error.
Because .then() also returns a Promise, we can chain multiple background tasks directly onto each other. If we rewrite our messy database Callback Hell from earlier, the sideways triangle flattens into a clean, readable straight line:
connectToDatabase()
.then(function(connection) {
return fetchUser(connection, "Naveen");
})
.then(function(user) {
return fetchUserPosts(user.id);
})
.then(function(posts) {
return calculateAnalytics(posts);
})
.catch(function(error) {
console.log("If ANY step fails, it instantly drops down here:", error);
});The Secret VIP Line (The Microtask Queue)
Promises are not just cleaner to read; they get special treatment inside the JavaScript engine. They do not wait in the normal line.
If you are building a neural network simulator for English alphabet recognition, and a user submits a completely blank drawing, your application must instantly process that input and update the screen to show 0% confidence. That specific data update is highly critical. It cannot get stuck waiting in a line behind a simple 2-second visual animation timer.
To handle this, JavaScript has two distinct waiting lines:

• The Macrotask Queue (The Regular Line): Older Web APIs like setTimeout drop their callbacks into this line.

• The Microtask Queue (The VIP Line): Modern Web APIs, specifically Promises, drop their finished callbacks into this priority line.
The Event Loop traffic controller will always completely empty the VIP Microtask Queue before it moves a single timer from the standard Regular line.

3. The Time-Pausing Manager (Async / Await)
Even with Promises flattening our code and giving us a VIP queue, chaining .then() over and over still looked slightly strange compared to normal, top-to-bottom programming.
Imagine you are ordering at the food street, but this time you have a magical remote control. You place your order, press “Pause,” and time freezes for you at the register. The rest of the street keeps moving, and the kitchen keeps cooking. When the food is placed on the counter, time unpauses for you, and you pick up your food.
What is it? Async / Await is the modern standard. It is not a new system; it is actually just a beautiful disguise placed over Promises.
What is it used ON? This is the most important rule: You can ONLY use await on a Promise. You cannot await a callback or a simple setTimeout.
How does it work? You place the word async in front of a function. This unlocks the magical await keyword inside that function.
// 1. Declare that this function has magical pausing powers
async function trainNeuralNetwork() {
try {
console.log("Starting model training..."); // 2. Pause exactly here until the Promise resolves
const layer1Result = await trainLayer(1);
console.log("Layer 1 done:", layer1Result);
// This line only runs after layer 1 is completely finished
const layer2Result = await trainLayer(2, layer1Result);
console.log("Layer 2 done:", layer2Result);
console.log("Model successfully trained!");
} catch (error) {
// Handle errors exactly like normal synchronous code
console.log("Training failed:", error);
}
}
trainNeuralNetwork();
When JavaScript hits the word await, it does not freeze the entire browser. It literally pauses that specific function, hands the Promise to the background, and steps out to do other things on the webpage. When the Promise finishes (and rushes through the VIP line), JavaScript steps back into the function and picks up exactly where it left off.
4. Doing It All At Once (Promise.all)
There is one flaw in our async/await code above if tasks do not depend on each other. If downloading an image takes 5 seconds, and fetching a text file takes 10 seconds, waiting for them one by one takes 15 seconds.
We should order them both at the exact same time.
When do we use it? Whenever you need to fetch multiple independent pieces of data concurrently.
How does it work? Promise.all() is a built-in helper that takes an array of multiple Promises, fires them all off into the background simultaneously, and waits until all of them are finished.
async function loadDashboard() {
try {
console.log("Fetching all data at once..."); // 1. Fire tasks into the background immediately
const imagePromise = fetchImage();
const textPromise = fetchText();
// 2. Pause here and await the Promise.all helper
const [image, text] = await Promise.all([imagePromise, textPromise]);
console.log("Dashboard ready!", image, text);
} catch (error) {
console.log("If either one fails, the whole process stops.");
}
}
Now, the total wait time is only 10 seconds (the length of the longest task). The background Web APIs handled the heavy lifting concurrently, and our single JavaScript thread just waited to pick up the array of final results.
Visual Summary
Writing asynchronous JavaScript is a journey of making code easier to read and execute.

• Callbacks: Passing functions inside functions. Perfect for DOM Events and Timers. Created deeply nested, unreadable triangles of code (Callback Hell) for sequential tasks.

• Promises: A standalone VIP priority line (Microtask Queue) for modern APIs like fetch(). They flatten Callback Hell into clean .then() chains.

• Creating Promises: Using new Promise(executor) and the resolve/reject buttons to manually build the factory that turns non-promise tasks into Promises.

• Async/Await: A sweet disguise strictly used on top of Promises. Allows us to pause functions locally, making code read exactly like standard, top-to-bottom logic.

• Promise.all: The tool used to fire off multiple Promises concurrently to massively speed up background work.
